summary:
I found the needle! The bug is caused by type coercion during the `min_rating` filtering. 

In `/app/utils.js`, the `min_rating` parameter extracted from the query string wasn't properly converted to a number:

```javascript
  if (searchParams.has('min_rating')) {
    // Read the minimum rating from query string
    query.minRating = searchParams.get('min_rating'); // <-- Passed as a string (e.g. "4")
  }
```

When this string is passed to `buildRatingRange(min, max)` in `/app/filter.js`:
```javascript
function buildRatingRange(min, max) {
  const range = [];
  for (let i = min; i <= max; i++) {
    range.push(i);
  }
  return range;
}
```

If `min` is `'4'`, the loop pushes the string `'4'`, then applies `i++` which effectively converts it to a number `5`, resulting in the `range` array being `['4', 5]`. 
Later, `[...].includes(p.rating)` relies on strict equality (`===`). Since `p.rating` is numerical (`4`), `'4' === 4` is false, and it misses matching those products.

I've fixed this by editing `/app/utils.js` to parse the parameter into a base-10 integer using `parseInt()`:

```javascript
  if (searchParams.has('min_rating')) {
    // Read the minimum rating from query string
    query.minRating = parseInt(searchParams.get('min_rating'), 10);
  }
```

Running `test.sh` now confirms the fix works:
```
Server running on port 3000
PASS: Rating filter returns correct results
```
